text:
part three of four:

iâ€™m in my mid 30â€™s, thereâ€™s the usual breakdown of old friendships, i had some difficult things happen within business relationships, iâ€™m divorced, there have been feuds in my family, #metoo , i have arguments with my son, i just realised iâ€™m at war with my tummy and digestion and iâ€™m trying to figure out how to dissolve sexism within the japanese tea culture and not just in japan.... .
a couple of months back i read conflict is not abuse by sarah schulman.  she makes the profoundly helpful distinction between normative conflict and abuse. normative conflict is the unavoidable and necessary result of independent people/countries living/existing together, abuse is when one person/state/species uses their power over another. the problem is the two get confused all the time. sometimes people experiencing normative conflict blow it out of proportion and claim they are being abused. sometimes people/counties perceive danger where it is not and overreact causing abuse/war. she suggests courageous, open communication is how to work through these situations so individual responsibilities can be owned, and violence and abuse avoided. 
the part of the book that was missing for me is what to do when the danger and abuse is real and conversation doesnâ€™t work. .

following this inquiry, where iâ€™ve gotten to thus far is putting love and appreciation into the things/people i want to and want me to, and moving away from what i canâ€™t resolve. me in there niggling for things/people to change does not help or create peace. 
all i can do is work on myself and the relationships that are worthy with the energy and resources i have. .
this does not mean only doing the nice things. iâ€™m doing the work to decolonize my mind, iâ€™m using the privilege that iâ€™ve been born with to rattle the pulpits of the patriarchy, environmental exploitation and racism within myself and my community. .
i do this work with tea.

text:
i need feminism because walking alone at night is a death wish. â 
because in order to be taken seriously i need to be the prettiest girl in the room instead of the most hardworking or smartest. â
 because when i go out, it will always be my fault if something happens. â 
because i am in love with my guy friendsâ€™ feminine traits and it takes way too long to show them. â 
because 1 in 5 females do not have access to feminine products. â 
because some people think that a tampon is more scary than rape. â 
because birth control has become a luxury. 
because i havent had a role model that looks like me until now. â
 because the hashtag #whyididntreport should not be trending. 
because i stand with women. â™€
#metoo #womensmarchdenver

text:
the last few days, i've received a couple of messages asking me to give my thoughts on the gillette commercial.

for those unfamiliar, this commercial is another attack on general masculinity, trying to portray our energy as inherently toxic.

it shows a kid crying to his mom because he got mean text messages from his bullies (gee, all of us boys are so harsh), then makes reference to the #metoo movements (we're all sexual savages too), and even suggests that kids wrestling,

or a man in the street approaching a woman he finds attractive is unacceptable, toxic behavior that's contributing to our poisonous society.

i see what they're doing... they're trying to promote a more "civilized" man,

but this "civilized" man is one who has been castrated,

he has had his power removed,

he's a yes-man cuck who can't make a decision, 
who doesn't have a purpose,

who just serves whatever alpha dog flexes on him.

thing is, 
when you try to promote this non-aggressive civilized man, and frown upon any behaviors that allow us to release our aggressive-energy (like rough-housing, sex, and even ragging on each other), you get more toxic masculinity, because this aggressive-energy ends up being released at inappropriate times.

the more you push down a man's aggressive-energy, the more pressure that builds, 
and it's only a matter of time before it blasts off.

if we give our men their power back, there will be less toxicity in the world, 
as men with their power can explore their dark side healthily,

they can stare their demons in the glaring red eyes,

they can wade in their shadows,

speaking of wading in the shadows,

few months back, i had a young man ask me how he could explore his shadows even more, which made me scratch my head, 
but, i answered him extensively. [link in bio]

text:
is there a #metoo version of the story of samson and delilah? i have been living with this works of art, samson redeemed (1947) by norman rockwell. it was commissioned by cecile b demille for his 1949 movie starring victor mature as samson and heddy lamarr as delilah. as i have talked with people about the work, my interpretation of the story has changed â€”Â for the better, i think.
...
the movie tells the version i grew up with: our hero, samson, succumbs to the vile temptress, who is working with the philistines to destroy him against godâ€™s purposes.
...
but, there is another, more nuanced interpretation of events. samson has great success due to a two-way promise with god. the success leads to hubris, and samson breaks his side of the bargain by taking on a lover, delilah, from among his sworn enemies. there is no future for delilah. she is a mistress at a time and place where women were considered property. she has no hope of being accepted among the israelites. and, she is perhaps seen as a conspirator by her own people, the philistines. she is a pawn â€” not a powerful villain â€” used by both samson and his enemies.
...
in the end, samson repents; pleading for his strength to come back. he does not blame delilah. in sure sign he is back on good terms with deity, samsonâ€™s strength is returned.
...
the benefit of this interpretation is not only that delilah may have been a victim herself â€” both of samsonâ€™s lust and the philistineâ€™s designs â€” but, that samson, despite his bad behavior, was redeemable.
...
one of the strengths of biblical narratives is their ability to find new depth and application with each generation. but, am i stretching the story too much for our moment? is there a relevant and faithful version of the story that could be told in me too era?

"they are independent, talented, intelligent young women. read more "they are our future leaders; our next generation of doctors, lawyers and entrepreneurs. text: as we remember mlk this weekend we must remember how civil rights activists of the past sought to love their enemies.  it is challenging for us to be warriors of love and light in the presence of so much hate, but it was done in the past and we must do it again. when i think about this in terms of the me too movement, i think about the challenge of survivors telling their stories while also forgiving their abusers.  how do we forgive those who have not apologized to us? who aren't sorry? who have hate in their heart for us? somehow, we must- so we can have the strength to keep fighting.

today i stand in my truth

as 2019 usher in new beginnings,
new cycles and new paradigm shifts... i have shifted my perspective and have a covenant with my creator to emerge into my true self which is divinity in a physical body... my mission is to assist with the healing of the old paradigms that are no longer serving humanity and must cease to exist. 
my calling is to assist my brothers & sisters that have experienced severe trauma and abuse as children.

text:
when prey becomes predator

young,
innocent & pure.

blood thirsty,
ravenous wolfâ€¦
lurking for the unprotected.

the beautiful butterfly
that is still in the cocoon,
clueless and empty,
not yet violated with hurt and pain.

only the light of love,
divinity dwelling within.

the predator smells the aura of virtue.

sinks his venomous fangs into the angelic flesh,
to purge innocence with death.

where there was once joy and wonderâ€¦
evil struckâ€¦
now only guilt and shame remain.

a domineering invasion of power
and manipulation,
becomes a life changing humiliation.

because the molester was once
the molested.

left alone and unprotectedâ€¦
force of perverted power usurped
over the powerless,
no one was there to protest this violation. Â victim filled with shame and humiliationâ€¦
confused how from perversion emerged
sick pleasure and sexual stimulation.

envious of the power of his manipulator,
vows to never be the victim againâ€¦
becomes infected with illusion and sin,
accepts his infestation and slithers to the dirt

to seek victims to infiltrate with his
poison of perversionâ€¦
this is now his truth.

wears the masks of father, brother, uncle, homie, lover and friend.

while simultaneously spreading his poison over and over again.

able to do so,
because shame and guilt is holding the
prey captiveâ€¦

however,
justice speaks and
truth has set the captive free!

truth has exposed the enemy,
light shines on darknessâ€¦

the preyâ€¦
the predatorâ€¦
healing steps in and
behold a new day!
@cosmic.empress

#survivingrkelly 
#metoo
#hollywood 
#thedevilsbedroom 
#whenpreybecomespredator
#poetry
#writers 
#muterkelly

text: so, i waited a minute to post my thoughts on the #muterkelly #metoomovement as a #domesticviolencesurvivor it was extremely painful for me to watch the #survivingrkelly documentary... i empathized so much, and could relate to the victims stories. i too, was that young, naive, inexperienced girl who believed and trusted a monster! a young girls 1st boyfriend/experience should be full of sweet & romantic memories. not abuse, manipulation, threats & physical abuse. but these #monsters such as #rkelly & my first boyfriend, prey on young, naive, inexperienced girls. so they can manipulate, mold, brainwash, & abuse physically & mentally. people on the outside looking in wonder, "how can she let it happen? why didn't she tell someone? why didn't she just leave?" the answer: #fear a deep fear for your life & that of your loved ones. so please don't ever judge! unless you've lived it. i'm thankful to god, that i'm alive, and here to tell my story. but so many other girls aren't that lucky. i'm thankful that i never ever again fell prey to any kind of abuse ever from anyone else in my life. it only happened to me with my first relationship, at the age of 17, & never again. i'm blessed to have always been surrounded by unconditional love and support. but so many are not as blessed. but this animal aka r. kelly is not the first, nor unfortunately will he be the last. therefore we need to arm & empower our daughters and sons with the wisdom to always, always respect themselves, their bodies, their minds. and demand that same respect from everyone else. as the mother of 2 young men, i've always instilled in them to #respect #praise #honor all young women, the same way they would expect their mom/sister/daughter to be treated. #itbeginsathome #leadbyexample #loveandprotect #muterkelly #metoo

we are heartbroken to hear of the first woman to be murdered by a man in 2019. 
say her name: aiia maasarwe. 
she was a young student in melbourne. she was walking home from catching the tram after a comedy show. she was on the phone to a family member. she should have been safe. 
how does this keep happening?
we know the answer to that. 
it keeps happening because male violence and male abuse is endemic in australian society due to gender inequality supported by social and cultural norms, the impossibility of facing criminal charges for violence and abuse until acts have become deplorable and the damage is already done, the resulting impotency and inappropriateness of police intervention, and the complete lack of help and support for victim-survivors. 
so the real question is, how much longer will we pretend not to know the answer?
statistics show that every week politicians take to delay acting on this issue out of fear of losing votes, another woman will die.
we are heartbroken to begin our 2019 tally:
ğŸ–¤

text: (cont..) australia gave women the right to vote and seek election in 1902, but which women? there were certainly no indigenous women among them. feminism in australia has been unable to represent intersectional and indigenous rights because we as white women do not have a lived experience of colonisation as oppressor, and have never experienced the level of femicide, forced sterilisation, sexual violence and abuse, our cultures, land and language dispossessed, or our children taken, as indigenous australian women have. the frameworks are very different. aus indigenous feminism sees decolonisation as integral - which pits them in many cases against white women running institutional feminist organisations because we donâ€™t understand enough about our history and what a decolonised aus might look like. then there is the issue of tokenism - bringing woc on board but then not being interested in how their opinions might alter â€˜what the focus of this group is.â€™ not allowing them to be leaders in their own right. considering their views too â€˜radicalâ€™ and threatening to the mainstream. these are real concerns - if change needs to happen, it happens slowly in most cases, and political savvy is needed. but by pandering to the status quo in â€˜order to change itâ€™, do we just protect it? and what of the women on the ground, working for free - white women - perhaps not so well off as people think, having nervous breakdowns because theyâ€™re dealing with rape and abuse stories every day, expected to â€˜fix it,â€™ then being attacked for being too corporate, too white, too much part of the problem? where is the empathy and support for them as leaders dealing with complex problems (without pay!!!)? these are questions iâ€™m still unpacking and i always appreciate your opinions; how and in what ways am i part of the problem and solution. letâ€™s talk.  #womenswave #womensmarch2019 artwork by @aluna.ink #isabellamanfredi #feminism #australianfeminism #indigenousfeminism #australianindigenousfeminism #womanism #humanrights #landrights #femicide #indigenousaustralia #metoo #menomore #nowaustralia

text:
when prey becomes predator

young,
innocent & pure.

blood thirsty,
ravenous wolfâ€¦
lurking for the unprotected.

the beautiful butterfly
that is still in the cocoon,
clueless and empty,
not yet violated with hurt and pain.

only the light of love,
divinity dwelling within.

the predator smells the aura of virtue.

sinks his venomous fangs into the angelic flesh,
to purge innocence with death.

where there was once joy and wonderâ€¦

evil struckâ€¦
now only guilt and shame remain.

a domineering invasion of power
and manipulation,
becomes a life changing humiliation.

because the molester was once
the molested.

left alone and unprotectedâ€¦
force of perverted power usurped
over the powerless,
no one was there to protest this violation.

victim filled with shame and humiliationâ€¦
confused how from perversion emerged
sick pleasure and sexual stimulation.

envious of the power of his manipulator,
vows to never be the victim againâ€¦
becomes infected with illusion and sin,
accepts his infestation and slithers to the dirt to seek victims to infiltrate with his
poison of perversionâ€¦
this is now his truth.

wears the masks of father, brother, uncle, homie, lover and friend.
while simultaneously spreading his poison over and over again.

able to do so,
because shame and guilt is holding the
prey captiveâ€¦

however,
justice speaks and
truth has set the captive free!

truth has exposed the enemy,
light shines on darknessâ€¦

the preyâ€¦
the predatorâ€¦
healing steps in and
behold a new day!

â€œin todayâ€™s society we are faced with many social norms and because of these, arbitrary ideals, men are in constant competition. whether it be a competition with others or themselves, men can only be sedated when they accept or know that they are the very best. this means men will do the most outrageous things to prove that they are the strongest, most intelligent, best looking, or any other quintessential desire. as a young ignorant male i did not understand how these roles played in our society until much later in my life. in the past when i had learned what these roles truly meant, i had endured countless situations where i would be in a competition with myself, trying to become my very best. after years of not accomplishing my goals of being my best self i have came to understand and accept that these ideals are what destroy peoplesâ€™ self-perception. in many cases we have already accomplished our greatest desire but due to â€œourâ€ human nature it will never be enough. what iâ€™m trying to say is, accept yourself for who you are because being like everyone else is boarding or lower your standards for others because nobody's going to be perfect and your â€œbenevolentâ€ desire of othersâ€™ attributes are what damages and destroys what really matters.â€

â€œfeminism is the radical notion that women are people.â€ ğŸ™ğŸ¼ i was moved several times today, honestly overcome with emotion. i need to do things in my life that awaken these senses more often. ::::::::::::: i was so impressed with the amount of young people out there. i was also impressed by the amount of men. there are so many great men who walk along side us every day. ğŸ™ŒğŸ¼ i am grateful for these men. 
human rights are a huge issue. if you donâ€™t see that in todayâ€™s world you need to open your eyes.  the needle has moved, yes, but not without sacrifice and not without a unified voice. we arenâ€™t the first to march and we wonâ€™t be the last. this weekend commemorates the worlds greatest civil rights leader- where would we be if it werenâ€™t for his voice?

text:
yes we sell skincare, but behind the team are real, hardworking, kind, loving women. as women, we are the creators of life 
on this earth. we are moms, aunts, sisters, daughters. we deserve better. equal pay, for equal work. same funding opportunities for female entrepreneurs as males. let's keep smashing those ceilings ladies.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
more women in leadership roles in the private sector, as well as the public. so we can start shaping policies that affect us; our health. our jobs. our lives and our families'. the decisions that affect us should be decided by us, and us alone. â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
we have a right to our bodies. we should have the right to say no, and be heard loud and clear. we should feel we can walk on the streets safely and be free from harm. â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
being a feminist, womanist does not make one a man-hating-bitch. that's not what being a feminist is. we love our men. if you believe each and every person has equal rights - you are a feminist. if you are proud to be a woman, you are a feminist. â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
and ladies, let's stop cutting each other down. we are stronger as one. let's be united and raise our voices for the things we believe in. let's elevate each other. let's make history for being the generation of women who said enough is enough ğŸ’ª. let's get lit ğŸ”¥ #womensmarch #thefutureisfemale
#feminist #girlpower #womenwithambition #nasty #femalepower #metoo #metoomovement

text: today is #womensmarch2019.  i could not be at the women's march this year.  i really wish that i could have been there with my sisters, but i'm taking a different path in 2019, and could not be happier about my choice.  after years of not fully understanding why i felt the way i did, i finally realized i needed to create big changes, take a leap of faith on myself, and explore.  i learned, probably later in life than a lot of people, that a woman can be her own hero, and walk her own hero's tale.  #metoo #timesup and #thewomensmovement played no small part in my confidence and encouragement to make my decision.  i knew i could not be the only person to want this life.  taking a step in to the unknown,  following my own truth to the potential dismay of others is the best way i can honor the women's movement.  i would like to find out if it is possible to create changes and still feel joy and connectedness.  it means that it reached me, and gave me the community that helped me embark on my journey.  this is me walking in to the promise of my own hero's tale.  i would even go so far as to call it magical.â¤ï¸

text:
a typical everyday call between my son max and i as he goes from work to the gymâ¤ï¸
me: hi boo! how was your day?
max: you know mom, same old, same old.
me: are you headed to the gym?
max: 35, 35!, 35! the speed limit is 35! yeah, i'm headed there now. what are you fucking stupid?  you're doing what? 20-25 in a 35 mph zone!
me: are you training someone tonight?
max: yeah, then i have to work out myself. holy shit! this idiot is parked in the middle of the fucking road! really? this is where you decide to park your car you stupid motherfucker! 
me: well, make sure you eat something, okay?
max: oh my god! you should see the front end of this car! it's completely bashed in! 
me: is it the car that was parked in the road? 
max: yes! i guess they couldn't pull over into a neighborhood like normal people! no, they just sit in the middle of the road and everybody driving has to slow down to look! 
me: well, i love you baby and be safe.
max: i'm surrounded by idiots. love you too mom â¤ï¸

text:
okay friends, i had to put my pride aside and make a gofundme because i need a lot of help and positive support. a hand full of you know what happened to me back in november. long story short i basically got sexually assaulted where i used to work which led me to attempt suicide. i have been in and out of psychiatric hospitals which led me to be broke and not have any money or a job for that matter. what makes the situation worse is that i will not have a place to live at the end of january. therefore that is why i made a gofundme because i am in a housing and financial crises. there is more to it but that is the short version. you can read more of what happened once you click the gofundme link. if you can't donate i understand but please share it. the more shares the better.

gahhh!!! my anxiety is through the roof. as i am typing this and sharing such a huge and sensitive thing in my personal life with all of you makes me worried and afraid of criticism and judgment. fear is written all over this post and i am sorry. i promise i am not seeking attention or trying to be selfish and make it seem like i'm bumming off of your guys' hard earned money. please forgive me if any of this is triggering for any of you. again i'm sorry and i promise my intention for this fundraiser is because i'm in need of help. thank you for everything.  #metoo https://www.gofundme.com/traumatic-event-leaving-me-financially-distraught

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

thatâ€™s what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him â€œwe can take it.â€ no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but itâ€™s a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then itâ€™s easy to come along for the ride. thereâ€™s no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. theyâ€™re both just characters on the television.

thatâ€™s what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. itâ€™s not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. itâ€™s that weâ€™ve lost the capacity to treat civics, governance, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

david karpf

text:
freedom is not free. 
it's sometimes easy to talk about the injustice we face each day in the workplace, but much more difficult to confront--especially when your family relies on your paycheck to meet their needs.  when asked why many of these great women will tell you that they do it for the kids.

text:
for the past week thoughts, and feelings have been igniting a fire of words burning to be expressed. content warning as i attempt to shine some light into the dark: discussion of violence against women and sexual assault.

last week i watched the 1st half of the surviving r kelly docuseries. why? i couldn't not. although i knew it would bring up anger and sadness and so many other emotions, these women have stories that need to be told and heard and felt, and that anger needs to translate into actions. to me, the most shocking part of it all was the fact this has been going on, these stories have existed for decades and basically been ignored. r kelly's use of power, manipulation and emotional abuse is sadly all too familiar, my heart ached for the young girls and women he preyed upon. but overwhelmingly i was angry that this has been allowed to go on and on and on for so long. people knew, and chose to do nothing.

on friday night i read about the horrific murder of aiia masarwe. it stopped me in my tracks. i'll be honest, i frequently walk around by myself late and night, and whilst i'm sometimes hyper aware, generally i feel safe. maybe this is because i know, statistically, the majority of violence against women occurs behind closed doors, perpetrated by people known to the victim. perhaps it's because i've lived through these experiences and reclaimed my life refusing to live in fear... what hit home was the fact that as women, we are never completely safe anywhere. it doesn't matter how careful you are, you can follow every safety tip known, but it doesn't guarantee you anything. aiia masarwe was attacked whilst on the phone to her sister, walking along a main road half a kilometre from her home. violence a ainst women occurs wherever someone chooses to commit it.

what we need to get clear on is this:
women are not raped or murdered because of the clothes they wear.
women are not raped or murdered because of how much they choose to drink or where they choose to go out.
women are not raped or murdered because of the choices they made travelling home or where they live.
women are raped and murdered because another person chose to rape and/or murder. cont'd

- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
- what we worked on was ... data harvesting programs where we would pull data from users of apps and all of their friend networks and run that data through algorithms that could profile their personality traits and other psychological attributes, wylie told cnnâ€™s don lemon monday evening.

wylie said the ultimate goal was to obtain information in order to exploit mental vulnerabilities that our algorithms showed that [facebook users] had.

in addition to wylie and cambridge analytica, accounts of cambridge analyticaâ€™s parent company, strategic communication laboratories, and those of a university of cambridge psychologist aleksandr kogan were also suspended.

the accounts were suspended because facebook received reports that data that had been shared with cambridge and wylie from koganâ€™s app may not have been completely deleted. koganâ€™s app was removed in 2015 and facebook said they had been previously provided certifications that the data had been deleted. - several days ago, we received reports that, contrary to the certifications we were given, not all data was deleted, facebook said friday. - we are moving aggressively to determine the accuracy of these claims. if true, this is another unacceptable violation of trust and the commitments they made. we are suspending scl/cambridge analytica, wylie and kogan from facebook, pending further information.

special counsel robert mueller asked cambridge analytica last fall to surrender emails from any of its employees who worked for the trump campaign, the wall street journal reported in december. the firm complied to the request.

diana stancy correll
washington examiner

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

thatâ€™s what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him â€œwe can take it.â€ no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but itâ€™s a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then itâ€™s easy to come along for the ride. thereâ€™s no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. theyâ€™re both just characters on the television.

thatâ€™s what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. itâ€™s not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. itâ€™s that weâ€™ve lost the capacity to treat civics, governance, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

david karpf
medium

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby," said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
in may 2018 i went on a mission: peace for the woman of uganda. thanks to the donations of many people i could visit the peace building projects of mensen met een missie.
personal stories the ladies shared devastated me. stories of multiple rape, domestic violence, female circumcision and forced marriage. i took photos of incredible strong woman who gave everything in the power to restore the peace in their communities. i asked them to show me their beauty and power in front of my camera lens. 
this special series is for you to be able to look in the eye of the unseen woman.

text:
mai bhagh kaur (punjabi: à¨®à¨¾à¨ˆ à¨­à¨¾à¨—à©‹) also known as mai bhago was a sikh woman who led sikh soldiers against the mughals in 1705.
she was an exceptionally skilled warrior on the battlefield and is revered as a saint in sikhism.
she was known for rallying the 40 sikhs (chali mukte) who abandoned guru gobind singh at the siege of anandpur sahib and bringing them back to fight. 
mai bhago stayed with guru gobind singh at talwandi sabo.
she may have adopted the garb of a nihang.
mai bhago became so spiritually absorbed that, according to the famous historical text suraj parkash, she would be absorbed in samadhi; her experiences were so profound that she forsook all her clothes and began living life nakedly as a sadhni.
the guru however ordered her to wear a small turban, kacchera, and wrap her self in a blanket as well as return to worldly ways and walk in maryada (code of conduct).
when the guru went to hazur sahib she became one of ten other bodyguards of the guru arming herself with a large lance (weighing about 102 pounds) and musket and did so in male attire.
mohan singh, jathedar of hazur sahib, in 1788 built a bunga (war tower) in the memory of mai bhag kaur.
name: Antiobjectificationist

la #donneemeraviglia di questa settimana Ã¨ di origine calabrese, laureata in fisica, madre di un figlio. lucia votano, dal 2009 Ã¨ la prima donna a dirigere i laboratori nazionali del gran sasso dell'istituto nazionale di fisica nucleare. con una carriera tutta all'interno dell'ifn intervallata dal soggiorno in germania e al cern, fa parte del peer review committee del coordinamento europeo per la fisica delle astro particelle, che nel settembre scorso ha delineato in un rapporto il futuro della ricerca astro particellare in europa. oggi coordina circa mille fisici provenienti da tutto il mondo che lavorano a una ventina di grandi progetti tra i quali quello che ha portato a dimostrare, insieme al cern di ginevra, l'esistenza del bosone di higgs.

text:
sexual harassment and being jabbed by dirty syringes are just some of the hazards commercial laundromat workers can face on a daily basis. the commercial laundromat industry services linens for hotels, hospitals and restaurants, and according to investigative reporter, @anniehylton, it is riddled with poor and dangerous working conditions. 
after a 6-month long investigation, annie joined @bradshowlive to share her findings, all published in her article â€œdirty laundryâ€ for @dissentmag. 
there is a â€œlack of basic safety equipment and training,â€ annie told @bernstein_brad on @bradshowlive. â€œthe women who i profiled in the piece, told me that they didnâ€™t even have gloves to wear, so when they were dealing with laundry, people would get poked by syringes and their fingers would start bleeding.â€ not only are the workers, many of them immigrant women, exposed to unsafe conditions, but sexual harassment also lurks many facilities. â€œone woman who i spoke to was sexually harassed for months and months and months by her manager,â€ annie said.

beliefs are masks we wear given by our parents, friends, educational institutions, churches, governments, social surroundings and they construct a reality by which most (if not all) of our decisions are made.
**
beliefs create our truths, they create how we perceive ourselves, they create limitations by which we are willing to "believe". **
beliefs limit the potentiality of creation and become subconscious inhibitors of limitless possibilities and potentials.
**
i believe to reach a place of untethered freedom and creation we must be willing to accept that the purpose of "belief" is to create a launching point by which we perceive from,not to create a place to judge perception from.
**
believe it or not - you wear many masks, a question which deserves answering is "who's mask are you wearing" **

text:
happy full moon and eclipse!
the wolf moon asks what changes need to be made. 
what space can you take?  unapologetically, passionately, confidently?
where are we apologizing for our existence or our requests?
where can we lean into the pack?
in what areas can we desire for desires sake?  just to feel and groove through desire?
it should be an action packed day with a surprise or two. 
what do you need?

text:
did they know? 
did they know how much they were taking away from me? 
did they know that their actions would bear such consequences for me?
did they know that they were breaking a human being?

did they know? 
that for years i wouldnâ€™t understand that what they did was wrong? 
that every day i foolishly thought that it was my fault? 
that i was drowning in shame because of their uncontrolled want?

did they know?
that, on some days, i would convince myself that it was all in my head? 
that those unwelcome touches were all lies i to myself fed? 
that the liquid that trickled down my thighs wasnâ€™t red?

do they know?
that they made all men alike predators in my eyes? 
that i find it impossible to place my trust in their lies? 
that for their wrongs against a little girl, a young woman still cries?

do they know? 
that what i wish for those vermin is not an easy death?
that they deserve to feel the full weight of what they did?
that i doubt that they are human enough to feel something akin to guilt?

text:
no matter how many books you read or how many degrees you have, i think there will always be an ounce of you that will never truly â€œgetâ€ how narcissists and psychopaths can treat people with such unconscionable disrespect.
.
you can learn why they are the way they are and you can learn how they operate. you can comprehend and you can sympathize. but i donâ€™t think most of us will ever truly understand them.
.
that can be frustrating as hell and it can lead you down some dangerous rabbit holes searching for answers youâ€™ll never find. my advice is to learn the basics (a book or two ought to do it in the beginning) then turn inward to your healing; owning and loving that frustration. donâ€™t allow that frustration to swell into contempt. instead, own it and embrace it as the exact quality that makes you a beautiful human being. ğŸ’›ğŸ¦‹

text:
gilletteâ€™s new ad â€œthe best a man can beâ€, that questioned its own tagline â€œthe best a man can getâ€ has wreaked havoc on the internet since itâ€™s release. as of 18th january 2019, the ad stands at 19m views with around 500k likes and a whopping 970k dislikes with more than 400k comments. the ad analyses how toxic masculinity spins the narrative of bullying, sexual harassment, objectification of women and mansplaining. it attempts to redefine real manliness so that boys find better role models in the men they look up to.
however, apparently, this â€œunnecessary misandrist moral lectureâ€ hasnâ€™t gone very well with our â€œmasculineâ€ viewers. as the ad challenges the notions of â€œboys will be boysâ€ and holding men accountable for their actions, men have flooded the internet with angry grunts of â€œlet boys beâ€ and â€œboycott gilletteâ€ - maybe because men arenâ€™t used to hearing what is right and what is wrong, maybe because they think that real men have the authority to do whatever they want and get away with it and maybe because being a decent human being threatens their fragile male ego.

the gillette ad is another beautiful example where men pant #notallmen and start whataboutism over women. even worse, the hashtag #letboysbe is a dangerous call to protect toxic masculinity. it is about reinforcing gender stereotypes of men being authoritative and dominating and considering kind, compassionate ones as less of a man. just looking at the comments section illustrates so much toxic masculinity in action *rolls eyes*.
it is horrific that in spite of such strong women empowerment movements and with the ongoing #metoo wave, something as subtle as a razor ad, that talks about doing away with toxic masculinity, has shattered the fragile male ego to the extent of being boycotted. the ad is being misinterpreted as anti-men, just like the whole feminism wave â€“ evident of the facts that not being a bully is anti-men, not harassing women is anti-men or not being a jerk is anti-men. in short, being human is being anti-men *slow claps*. the irrational hate and anger of men, towards something that merely asks them to not be awful humans, immediately justifies the very existence of this ad.

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
a year and one day ago, i sat in my living room in tears of rage making a sign, as i watched a former student confront our mutual abuser in court. 
a year ago today i woke up, and wrote a personal statement of my own to be read for the judge and for the world. 
i took my sign, met strangers at panera and marched. it was the first time i physically spoke about my abuse to strangers. when two individuals dressed in spartan gear came up to me, i looked them square in the eyes and told them michigan state needed to be held accountable for their lack of action in preventing my abuse. up until that point, i had never felt more empowered. 
a year ago today, my new friend miguel took this picture of me, and it was shared by the huff post, by olympians, and by my sister survivors. 
it has been a year of ups and downs, years of rage, tears anxiety, tears of sadness and tears of happiness. 
but i will not rest and i will keep marching until the day institutions are held accountable for the sexual violence that occurs under their watch. i will keep marching for every victim who feels they are unheard. 
i see you, i hear you, i believe you. .
.
.
#metoo #metoomsu #womensmarch2018 #womensmarchchi #survivor #believewomen

text:
i made a decision to stop hiding.
iâ€™m sorry for not showing up sooner.
i didnâ€™t want to say who i really was.
i felt scared to embrace the depth of myself. how much wisdom and power i had inside of me. how dark and unheard of my experience has been.
i tried for so long to keep it suppressed and hidden. i was even willing to bury it under more pain and suffering, struggle and chaos. just to avoid getting to the core of it and really surrendering, to the truth, my truth.
i began to write my story, the real one, as it is, how i felt it, how i see it.
i finally had the willingness to write it, to sit with it, to own it, to become it, to embrace it.
and it took a lot of strength. so much strength that i didnâ€™t know i had in me.
i didnâ€™t want to be that person, i didnâ€™t want to be this person.
i was avoiding it for so long, and i was trying to be and do anything but what was really the heart of the matter, why i was really here and what message i had to share.
the story that would change the world and change lives â€” my story.
i hid under the fear that maybe it wouldnâ€™t matter to anyone, that maybe no one would care and it wasnâ€™t worthwhile.
but that was a big fat lie. of course this mattered, of course people would care, of course this would help people.
it was my own sabotaging ways that were the problem blocking me, not the dismissal of others.
in fact, i could feel people waiting for me to step forward with this medicine, with my truth, with the truth of who i really was.
the truth about who i was before the event, who i was after the event, and who i am now.
iâ€™m sorry, but i had to come home to my story, first.
i had to come to terms with my truth first, before i was ready to share it. before i was ready to actually be here with you, to be here as the real me, the one who went through the trauma, the one who suffered and survived. the one who was hidden behind self-betrayal and abandonment, disguised as many other distracting things.
i wasnâ€™t allowed to step forward until now. fear held me back, in a cage. but i broke free.
i finally broke free.
it took my whole heart to get here.
yeah, i was scared that my family would read about what i was up to.

text:
day four, final day of installation!
.
the panty project is an ongoing social practice project. participants, womxn and those who identify as womxn, courageously share with me their stories of experienced gendered transgressions and violent aggressions, whether cultural and/or interpersonal. participants write a word or phrase onto the panel of their selected undergarment; i hand-embroider over their mark-making and photograph them as if they have been taken off. this work addresses the inherent misogyny within our language, and the consequential "essestializing" of womxn, which reduces womxn, and those who identify as womxn, to "less than." this work is about healing and transcendence. 
womxn's long-silenced voices must be heard.
.

text:
un libro da leggere, sottolineare, e regalare. uno di quei testi in cui passare dal pianto alla risata nel giro di poche righe. una voce che da modo al femminismo gioioso di esser condiviso e abbracciato, in cui si chiede a donne e uomini di fanne parte. si parla di corpo, linguaggio e di tutte quelle pratiche per diventare attive di un movimento essenziale. per liberarci dagli stereotipi che vede le femministe incazzate e rabbiose ma che vuole coinvolgere tutti, senza esclusione di genere, sesso e orientamento. un libro per diffondere un femminismo fuori dalle porte degli addetti ai lavori, di ispirazione e soprattutto di grandi consigli pratici.
insomma, rimbocchiamoci le mani e facciamo tutti la nostra parte. ogni giorno, per creare un cultura femminista utile a tutti. donne e uomini compresi. .
.
.

text:
the penn (students newspaper at university of pennyslvania) wrote: "clothing is apparently a big deal in this world of sexual harassment and assault. but it shouldn't be. focusing so much on a personâ€™s dress is not only taking away from his or her experiences, but it also continues the idea that victims are at fault for their circumstances." â£â£
â£â£
"the concept that women should avoid dressing â€œlike slutsâ€ in order not to be victimized is nothing new. women begin to receive this message from a young age. teens â€” even children,  are sexualized for everything from their bare shoulders to their â€œtoo tightâ€ pants." â£â£
â£â£
i try to talk about this topic as much as i can. it is uncomfortable because there will always be disagreements, and the reason behind those disagreements is because it has been ingrained in our brains to sexualize women's bodies. one of the clearest examples is when people label mothers breastfeeding in public as "inappropriate" (even though they're feeding their babies, nothing sexual). the public sees women's breasts, and bodies,  as sexual objects. it is uncomfortable to talk about but change begins by talking about these uncomfortable things with friends, family and your social media followersâ€” in person and/ or through social media posts.  who knows, it might give people a different perspective? â£â£
â£â£
unfortunately there are still people who think that we should teach victims â€” which are mostly women , â€” how to dress properly instead of teaching rapists to not rape.  that should change. we should teach our sons to be a proper human being and the importance of consent. if you are a victim of rape, it is not your fault.  i stand with you. i encourage you to read this article by @the.independent about the display of rape victims outfits. it is eye opening to show us that even people wearing socially labelled as "appropriate outfits" are victims. please also read the jakarta post article about the importance of psychological help for rape survivors. both links are in bio. â£â£
#timesup #metoo

text:
one of my favorite experiences this past trip was facilitating a workshop in samut prakan with migrant mothers and children from myanmar. under dhamma theatre west and ruth pongstapgone, the in us, between us, around us: creativity workshop for growing the environment of mother and child was designed.

the workshop was created to inspire awareness of the relationship between mother and child, to grow the strength of that relationship through creativity and imagination. the workshop aimed to provide a safe space in which to explore the use of movement, music and breath as way for children and mothers to create environments together. 
visual art activities, including portrait making photography, offered mothers and children a new way to see and express their feelings for each other. a special thank you to pawaluk suraswadi for her help and knowledge.

i cannot wait to share all i have learned from my mentors and the communities. i am currently finishing up a research blog covering the first two phases of my learning under ajahn pongstaphone! i hope to share it with everyone soonğŸ’•

the woman facing us walked backwards, drumming, swaying to the beat, leading, calling the rhythms, looking super joyful. she really inspired me. ğŸ¥
my friend @kellybreauxfitness , is an amazing drummer and always brings her drum to the gatherings, marches, rallies, protests, and yesterday was no different. she fits right in with this talented group.
ğŸ¥
i, on the other hand, have very little experience on the drum, but i brought my little jembe anyway. it's really hard to drum, walk, keep anything more complicated than a 1,2,3,4 beat (for me, at least), and sway in synch with a group. i am truly grateful i was included.
ğŸ¥
inclusion. the big take away message from this year's women's march. we are battling against an administration hell bent on dividing, separating, excluding, shaming, putting up walls. i really appreciate all of those who came to the  stage and spoke about community, inclusion, and acceptance.
ğŸ¥

text:
rani mehra was true representation of an indian girl in middle-class household, who is mostly vulnerable, shy, soft-spoken, under-confident, but also wishes good for people surrounding her. and although she never spoke about it, but she aversed being controlled by others. she enjoyed her freedom to drink and dance at her will, wear whatever she felt like, visit new places and encounter new adventures.
she loved to cook for others, easily trusted people around her, and her love was extremely passionate. and although shy, she was not an introvert and enjoyed dancing with a group or when she was drunk. in fact, she loved having fun with people whenever she had an opportunity. her extroversion and inner thoughts could be clearly seen when she was drunk.
further, she always tried to put her brave face on even during troublesome situations, but had no problem in breaking down into tears when she was free and her emotions always emerged in her mother tongue.
rani was extremely friendly in her etiquettes and hardly over-thought about situations or her decisions, letting things flow smoothly. and whenever proven wrong, she was quick to learn from her mistakes and made sure to never repeat the same.
rani was relatable for some and motivational for others, but had connect with every indian girl.

ps: indians sab cheez mein best hai. kissing mein bhi indians hi best hai! kabhi emraan hashmi ka naam nahi suna?

pps: kangana ranaut secured national and filmfare awards for best actress for her portrayal of rani mehra, and given its wide appeal and connection with indian society, the film is being remade in tamil, telugu, kannada and malayalam.

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
yesterday i cofacilitated a closed discussion for black women called "unpacking r. kelly." though it was in the aftermath of the documentary, we truly focused on the larger systems at play in our own experiences. i am so proud of the brave work we did in not only defining what sexual abuse has looked like for us but crafting a vision for the difference we would like to see going forward. i shared in my ig story yesterday that i love black people soooo much. i love us beyond the expectations that are in place that says that's just how it's always been. i love us enough to imagine a future that i have never seen but know in my bones is possible. this means asking the hard questions, sitting with the uncomfortable answers and doing some real reflection. i'm ready to make the ancestors proud and heal generational trauma for the sake of everyone in my lineage. stay tuned for a follow up event that is open to all genders. we will absolutely be keeping this conversation alive and engaging the community in this important work. thank you again to @soulzandgspotz and @alternativewaves for making this space possible. i'm so grateful for our paths crossing!

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

veli pashaâ€™s page by louis duprÃ© (1789â€“1837). veli pasha was the oldest son of ali pasha of ioannina, known for both his brutality and generosity (byron was his happy guest). ali pasha is known to have ordered a woman blamed for one of his sons' adultery sewn into a sack and drowned. byron retold this story many times, with varying degrees of his own involvement to embellish the tale. veli pasha (not the adulterer), like his father, was fond of boys. 39 or 40 at the time of byron's visit, veli called the poet "beautiful boy." ğŸ

text:
what does #metooâ¤ï¸ mean to you?

for some, it means the awkward moment when we have to fend off unwanted advances, of a man. for others itâ€™s being the only girl in a room full of inappropriate banter between inappropriate men. 
to some, it means something completely different. some women are destroyed mentally and physically by the person they loved and trusted most. these women are no different than you and i. they woke up, on their wedding day, with hopes and dreams of fairy tale endings. what happens when life becomes anything but a fairytale? where are we, as a society when these women need us the most? people who know me, know i almost never share these things, but this one hits so close to home that i have no choice, but to share with others! if everyone reading this gave as little as $5, this beautiful young mom could start to get her life back... think about that!  letâ€™s remind her she is not alone and not forgotten! give what you can! thanks! link in bio. #metoo #metoomovement #putyourmoneywherehermouthis #abusesurvivor #abusedwomen

text:
this is a lot and and itâ€™s pretty personal so if you read it - thank you.
.
i want to start by saying that not all men are actively creating this current harmful and degrading culture for women. i have many wonderful men in my life. and the #metoo movement and feminism need men to speak with us, because we are far more powerful together.
.
i want to share a few reasons why i march in support of #metoo and womenâ€™s rights:
1. i was assaulted while in college - i was not wearing a short skirt nor was i drunk - and this gives me a chance to publicly say #metoo and join the millions of voices around the world in solidarity so that the next nassar canâ€™t leave a wake of unbelieved victims.
2. a history of injustice and a trajectory of the same globally for women in court rooms, child brides, humans being trafficked - people should be protected and treated with full respect regardless of gender, religion, sexual orientation, race...
3. we are not that far removed from illegal birth control for single women or men-only universities - and are not removed at all from people like nassar and weinstein using their influence and power to manipulate and hurt so many women
4. our country has elected a man as president - to the highest office of power and honor - who publicly admits (and brags) to having violated women as a result of his status. calling attention and paying attention is crucial.
.
there are so many reasons and these are just a few, but it truly is empowering to join the voices of friends and strangers alike to speak up for all people.
.
anita hill and christine blasey ford - 20 years apart, with the same familiar story. both sets of male dominated courts did not hear them. but we did. the same conclusion now does not mean the same old story. they were not believed. and yet the wake that they both created has changed so much. and they are reasons why we march - to continue raising awareness on the change that is still needed.
.
if you made it here, thanks so much for listening.
.
#metoo #womensmarch #womensmarch2019 #womensmarchnyc #nyc #imwithher

text: it took 8 years (a quarter of my life), 4 countries, and the me too movement to get our play produced in the art mecca of the world. in 2011, dominique strauss kahn sexually assaulted his chambermaid in the sofitel hotel in nyc. in 2012, my dad and i took his play to a private reading in a basement in paris followed by a run at the edinburgh fringe festival with a 4 star review in @thetimes we tried for the west end in london and off-broadway in nyc to no avail. we tried to turn it into a cle ethics credit, but not enough lawyers signed up to come on a tuesday night. six years later, we braved up and had another go - and this time, it was picked up and launched into production! danke dir berlin. you are brave and bold and most certainly the art capitol of the world! #metoo #metoomovement #playwright #theatre #bts #politicaltheatre #onlocation #onstage #producer #perseverance #riseup #shinealight #globalcitizen #fightthegoodfight #dsk #lawyer #womensmarch #togetherwerise #a21 #presidentialsuite #nyc #berlin

text:
everyone says love yourself like it's this easy task.  when in fact, it's a battle. who knew identifying that you don't feel worthy could be so painful. or that feeling of inadequacy makes you find comfort in another person filling a void, regardless of how terrible they are to you. it took many years to realize what it meant to love myself. it's still a battle, especially in those times of frustration or triggers. when i learned to love myself, i learned to make more quality decisions for myself. i chose to put myself first, rather than accommodate everyone else. i learned to stop pushing people away who care and remove toxic people. 
i realized i spent too much time learning about others, and what they love and hate, than focusing on caring about what i love and hate. i choose to be my own best friend that looks out for me. i protect me. i love me. and, i know i am worthy. .
.
.
.
.
.

2nd time read! .
last year was #gameon with the #metoo movement but it wasn't just about punishing offenders and making the world pay attention.

it's all here, in the pages of this book. thanks to the lovely @adiatdisu for gifting it to me.
